    "call_para": null,
    "edits": [
     {
      "old_exact": " 3\n\nThe parties have not cited Section 30.1–12–01, N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–101], which provides that property devolves upon death to the devisees or heirs. In Feickert v. Frounfelter, 468 N.W.2d 131, 132 (N.D.1991), we construed the statute to mean that property passes upon death, not upon distribution. However, both the statute and Feickert recognize that devolution is subject to administration, and the personal representative has “power over the title” during the administration of the estate. Feickert, supra, 468 N.W.2d at 132; Section 30.1–18–11, N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–711]. The personal representative has specific authority to sell or dispose of property of the estate, see Section 30.1–18–15(6) & (2), N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–715], and the provisions of Section 30.1–12–01 do not restrict that authority.\n",
      "new_exact": "\n\n3\n\n. The parties have not cited Section 30.1–12–01, N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–101], which provides that property devolves upon death to the devisees or heirs. In Feickert v. Frounfelter, 468 N.W.2d 131, 132 (N.D.1991), we construed the statute to mean that property passes upon death, not upon distribution. However, both the statute and Feickert recognize that devolution is subject to administration, and the personal representative has “power over the title” during the administration of the estate. Feickert, supra, 468 N.W.2d at 132; Section 30.1–18–11, N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–711]. The personal representative has specific authority to sell or dispose of property of the estate, see Section 30.1–18–15(6) & (2), N.D.C.C. [U.P.C. § 3–715], and the provisions of Section 30.1–12–01 do not restrict that authority.\n",
      "verified_count": 1
